<DOC><DOCNO> AP890310-0087 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0934EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Berlin 1stLd-Writethru a0516 03-10 0425</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Berlin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0434</SECOND><HEAD>Leftist Party Joins Social Democrats In West Berlin Coalition</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with business threatening to leavecity because of environmentalists. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD><BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A leftist party today agreed to join the SocialDemocrats in forming a coalition government in West Berlin, a movethat businesses said could cause them to leave the divided city.   The coalition of the left-leaning Social Democrats and the farleft Alternative List, the West Berlin equivalent of the anti-NATOGreens Party, also has prompted Conservative West German politiciansfrom Chancellor Helmut Kohl on down to warn of dire consequences forthe city.   Businessmen have opposed the Alternative List's insistence ontighter environmental controls and claim the leftist group creates abad climate for investment. Some businessmen warned they may leavethe city, which had been dominated by Kohl's Christian DemocraticUnion.   The Social Democrats and the Christian Democrats won 55 seatseach in the West Berlin legislature in the Jan. 29 elections.   The Alternative List won 17 seats and the far-right RepublicanParty stunned many West Germans by winning 11 seats.   After weeks of sometimes tense talks, negotiators for the twoleftist parties announced agreement on the details of the governmentearly today. The agreement was expected to win easy formal approvalfrom the full membership of both parties within days.   The agreement outlined to the news media gives the AlternativeList three senators, who are the equivalent of Cabinet ministers inother West German state systems. As a result, the far-leftists willbe in charge of programs for the environment, city development,education, sports, families and youth.   The Alternative List also has advocated more curbs on the police,limits on motor vehicle use and more government-subsidized housing.   Under the leftist coalition government, Social Democrat WalterMomper will become the new mayor of West Berlin. He will replaceEberhard Diepgen, whose Christian Democrats suffered severe setbacksin elections on Jan. 29.   The Christian Democrats had been actively promoting businessdevelopment in West Berlin to help end the isolation of the city 90miles inside communist East German territory.   The United States has promoted greater airline access to WestBerlin and has suggested that the city could be the site of U.N.meetings as well as world conferences on human rights, arms controland other issues.   The far-right Republican Partym which has called for the ousterof foreign workers and asylum seekers from West Berlin, is excludedfrom the governing coalition.</TEXT></DOC>